   <titles>
      <title>Preview: Orientation</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>We introduce the concept of orientation of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math> as a means for distinguishing an object in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math> from its mirrored image. In this preview we only discuss the visualizable dimensions 1,2,3.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <strong>1-dimensional orientation</strong> – An orientation of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr</latex>
                  </math> is given by a nonzero vector <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x} = (x)</latex>
                  </math>. We say</para.body>
            </para>
            <table align="center"
                   border="3"
                   bordercolor="Maroon"
                   cellpadding="2"
                   cellspacing="2">
               <row>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                           </math> represents the positive orientation of <math>
                              <latex>\RNr</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>if <math>
                              <latex> x&gt; 0 </latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>\omega(\Vect{x}) = +1</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                           </math> represents the negative orientation of <math>
                              <latex>\RNr</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>if <math>
                              <latex> x &lt; 0 </latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>\omega(\Vect{x}) = -1</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </table>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <strong>2-dimensional orientation</strong> – An orientation of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> is given by a pair of 
				<subordinate>
                     <hot>noncolinear vectors</hot>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>`noncolinear' means: don't lie on one line; in other words: point in distinct directions</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </subordinate>
                  <math>
                     <latex>(\Vect{x} , \Vect{y} )</latex>
                  </math>. We say</para.body>
            </para>
            <table align="center"
                   border="3"
                   bordercolor="Maroon"
                   cellpadding="2"
                   cellspacing="2">
               <row>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>( \Vect{x} , \Vect{y} )</latex>
                           </math> represents the positive orientation of <math>
                              <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>if the lesser of the two angles from <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                           </math> to <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                           </math> occurs in the counterclockwise direction</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>\omega(\Vect{x} , \Vect{y} ) = +1</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>( \Vect{x} , \Vect{y} )</latex>
                           </math> represents the negative orientation of <math>
                              <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>if the lesser of the two angles from <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                           </math> to <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                           </math> occurs in the clockwise direction</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>\omega(\Vect{x} , \Vect{y} ) = -1</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </table>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <strong>3-dimensional orientation</strong> – An orientation of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math> is given by a triple of 
				<subordinate>
                     <hot>noncoplanar vectors</hot>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>`noncoplanar' means: don't lie in one plane</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </subordinate>
                  <math>
                     <latex>(\Vect{x} , \Vect{y} , \Vect{z} )</latex>
                  </math>. We say</para.body>
            </para>
            <table align="center"
                   border="3"
                   bordercolor="Maroon"
                   cellpadding="2"
                   cellspacing="2">
               <row>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>( \Vect{x} , \Vect{y} , \Vect{z} )</latex>
                           </math> represents the positive orientation of <math>
                              <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>if it is possible to align your right hand's thumb with <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                           </math>, its index finger with <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                           </math>, and its 
						<subordinate>
                              <hot>middle finger</hot>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>without harming your hand</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </subordinate>
						with <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{z}</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>\omega(\Vect{x} , \Vect{y} , \Vect{z} ) = +1</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>( \Vect{x} , \Vect{y} , \Vect{z} )</latex>
                           </math> represents the negative orientation of <math>
                              <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>if it is possible to align your left hand's thumb with <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                           </math>, its index finger with <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                           </math>, and its 
						<subordinate>
                              <hot>middle finger</hot>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>without harming your hand</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </subordinate>
						with <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{z}</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>\omega(\Vect{x} , \Vect{y} , \Vect{z} ) = -1</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </table>
            <para>
               <para.body>We also explain the relationship between orientation of 3-space and rotation about an oriented axis according to the right/left hand rule.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </body>
